library(cjEuclid)

1 Functions

The package has three functions and a wrapper.

1.1 lm_euclid

lm_euclid fits a model with interactions and quadratic terms given a formula

For instance:

data <-
 fabricatr::fabricate(N = 40,
                      butter = rnorm(N), 
                      guns = rnorm(N),
                      rating  = -(butter^2 + (guns-.3)^2 + .2*rnorm(N)))

model <-  lm_euclid(rating ~ guns + butter, data)
## The estimated A matrix is  positive semi definite
## The A matrix:
##               guns      butter
## guns    0.97425751 -0.02287668
## butter -0.02287668  1.02234703
model |> tidy() |> kable(digits = 2)
term estimate std.error statistic p.value conf.low conf.high df outcome
(Intercept) -0.06 0.04 -1.42 0.16 -0.15 0.03 34 rating
guns 0.61 0.03 20.93 0.00 0.55 0.67 34 rating
butter -0.01 0.03 -0.29 0.78 -0.07 0.06 34 rating
I(guns^2) -0.97 0.02 -46.03 0.00 -1.02 -0.93 34 rating
I(butter^2) -1.02 0.03 -34.18 0.00 -1.08 -0.96 34 rating
guns:butter 0.02 0.03 0.90 0.37 -0.03 0.07 34 rating

The function simply creates the Euclidian formula and passes it to lm_robust.

You can provide any additional lm_robust functions you want as additional arguments, for instance, weights, cluster, blocks.

1.2 euclid_fits

euclid_fits is a simple helper to generate fitted values for a model given specified ranges and length

predictions_df <- 
  euclid_fits(formula = rating ~ guns + butter, model, data, lengths = c(2,3))

predictions_df |> kable(digits = 3)
guns butter utility
-2.350 -1.702 -9.737
-2.350 0.371 -7.048
-2.350 2.444 -13.146
2.709 -1.702 -8.605
2.709 0.371 -5.676
2.709 2.444 -11.534

1.3 euclid_plot

euclid_plot call ggplot to plot the predicted fits and adds ideal points

predictions_df <- 
  euclid_fits(formula = rating ~ guns + butter, model, data, lengths = c(20,20))

euclid_plot(predictions_df, X = "guns", Y = "butter")

1.4 cjEuclid

cjEuclid wraps these functions and returns a list with the model, the fitted values, and the graph.

results <- cjEuclid(rating ~ guns + butter, data)
## The estimated A matrix is  positive semi definite
## The A matrix:
##               guns      butter
## guns    0.97425751 -0.02287668
## butter -0.02287668  1.02234703
results$graph

2 Examples

The functions include multiple arguments to allow graphing multiple dimensions. Here we illustrate plotting 2 dimensions with faceting by a third.

# Data has three dimensions and two observations per subject

data <-
 fabricatr::fabricate(
   ID = add_level(20),
   choice = add_level(2,
                      A = rnorm(N), B = rnorm(N), C = rnorm(N),
                      W = -(A^2 + (B-.3)^2 + (C --.67)^2) + .2*rnorm(N) + 3*A*B))


results <- 
  cjEuclid(W ~ A + B + C,
           fixed_effects = ~ ID,
           se_type = "stata", 
           data = data,
           X = "B",
           Y = "C",
           Col = "A",
           mins = c(-2, -2, -2),
           maxs = c(2, 2, 2),
           lengths = c(5, 25, 35),
           y_vals = c("little", "some", "much"),
           x_vals = c("This", "that", "there"))
## The estimated A matrix is not positive semi definite
## The A matrix:
##             A           B           C
## A  0.99860623 -2.95717928  0.00721775
## B -2.95717928  1.04797068 -0.01309017
## C  0.00721775 -0.01309017  1.02932337
results$graph

more ggplotting can be done later:

results$graph + 
  ylab("another label and a flip") + coord_flip() 
## Coordinate system already present. Adding new coordinate system, which will replace the existing one.

2.1 4 d

# Data has three dimensions and two observations per subject

data <-
 fabricatr::fabricate(
   ID = add_level(20),
   choice = add_level(2,
                      X1 = rnorm(N), X2 = rnorm(N), X3 = rnorm(N), X4 = rnorm(N), 
                      W = -(X1^2 + (X2-.3)^2 + (X3 --.67)^2 + X4^2)  + .2*rnorm(N)))


results <- 
  cjEuclid(W ~ X1 + X2 + X3 + X4,
           fixed_effects = ~ ID,
           se_type = "stata", 
           data = data,
           X = "X1",
           Y = "X2",
           Row = "X3",
           Col = "X4",
           mins = c(-2, -1, -2, -2),
           maxs = c(2, 1, 2, 2),
           lengths = c(35, 25, 5, 3),
           y_vals = c("little", "some", "much"),
           x_vals = c("This", "that", "there"))
## The estimated A matrix is  positive semi definite
## The A matrix:
##             X1          X2          X3          X4
## X1  1.02208406  0.02572174  0.01329216 -0.02196230
## X2  0.02572174  1.04187897 -0.03655335 -0.07035768
## X3  0.01329216 -0.03655335  1.06258573  0.02210962
## X4 -0.02196230 -0.07035768  0.02210962  1.00875372
results$graph

2.2 Subgroup plots

Can be done by treating a subgroup as a variable, by stitching multiple plots together, or by running lm_euclid adn cj_Euclid on multiple groups and then applying the plot function with the group as a dimension.

2.3 Example when \(A\) is not positive semi definite

data <-
 fabricatr::fabricate(N = 40,
                      butter = rnorm(N), 
                      guns = rnorm(N),
                      rating  = -(butter^2 - (guns-.3)^2 + .2*rnorm(N)))

cjEuclid(rating ~ guns + butter, data)$graph
## The estimated A matrix is not positive semi definite
## The A matrix:
##               guns      butter
## guns   -1.03429828 -0.03155689
## butter -0.03155689  0.97908949
